div.div:
The
8080 memory read cycle
is illustrated below with the custom bus signals. The address bus is set up early and held stable while the read strobe is active. The
SMEMR#
signal (active low
Memory Read
) is asserted after the address is valid, and the CPU raises
pDBIN
(Processor Data Bus IN) to enable data input from memory. The data bus is driven by the memory (RAM) during the read – in the diagram, an example byte
0x5A
is returned. The
XRDY
line is used to insert wait states: when
XRDY
is held low, the CPU elongates the cycle by adding a wait state
Tw
(as shown). Once
XRDY
goes high (ready), the cycle proceeds to completion (T3) and the CPU latches the memory data.

Tw (Wait):
Optional wait state inserted if
XRDY
= 0 (memory not ready).
SMEMR#
and
pDBIN
remain asserted, and the address stays valid, effectively stretching T2 until
XRDY
returns high.

div.div:
T3:
Memory places the data byte on the data bus. The data bus becomes valid (in the example,
0x5A
) with
pDBIN=1
meaning the CPU is reading. The CPU samples the data at the end of T3. After this,
SMEMR#
is de-asserted (goes high) and
pDBIN
drops, ending the read cycle (the address bus may change for the next cycle after a brief hold time).

div.div:
The
8080 memory write cycle
is shown below. The address bus is again asserted early (T1) and held stable while the data is written. The CPU indicates a write cycle by driving the
SWO#
line low (Write Out status, active low) – this tells the system that the data bus will be driven by the CPU. The
MWRT#
signal (Memory Write strobe, active low) is then asserted to actually write the data to RAM. The CPU drives the data bus with the output data (for example,
0xA5
) by the final T-state of the cycle, so that the memory can latch it when
MWRT#
is active.

div.div:
T2:
The 8080’s status lines indicate a
write
cycle (
SWO#
is pulled low, meaning a write operation). The data bus is not yet driven with the final data (the CPU may be internally preparing the byte).

div.div:
T3:
The CPU places the output data on the data bus and asserts
MWRT#
low to write.
MWRT#
is the actual write strobe to memory – it goes low when data is valid, allowing the addressed RAM location to latch the byte (here
0xA5
). After the data is latched (end of T3),
MWRT#
goes high and
SWO#
returns high, completing the cycle. (If the memory wasn’t ready,
XRDY
would insert wait states similar to the read cycle, stretching the cycle before T3 until ready.)
